1.What is String in Java?
String is a class in Java used to represent a sequence of characters.
String name = "Vikram";

2.Why String is immutable?
String is immutable for security, performance, and memory optimization (String Pool).
Once created, it cannot be changed.
String s = "Hello";
s.concat(" World");

System.out.println(s);  // Hello (not changed)

3.What is String Pool?
String Pool is a special memory area in heap where unique string literals are stored to save memory.
String s1 = "Java";
String s2 = "Java";

System.out.println(s1 == s2);  // true (same reference)

4.Difference between == and .equals()
== compares references, while .equals() compares actual content.
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = new String("Java");

System.out.println(s1 == s2);        // false
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));   // true

5.Difference between String, StringBuilder, StringBuffer
String is immutable, StringBuilder is mutable & fast (not thread-safe), StringBuffer is mutable & thread-safe (slow).
Feature
String	StringBuilder	StringBuffer
Mutability	Immutable	mutable	mutable
Thread-safe	No	No	Yes
Performance	Slow	Fast	Slower

6.How many ways to create String?
Two ways: using String literal and using new keyword.
String s1 = "Java";                 // literal
String s2 = new String("Java");     // new keyword

7.What is intern() method? (Optional but good)
intern() method returns reference from String Pool if it exists, otherwise adds it to the pool.
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = s1.intern();

System.out.println(s1 == s2);  // false
